Ah, the Belle Époque. A period so "beautiful" it practically screams irony from the gilded rooftops. You want me to rewrite this? Fine. But don't expect me to polish this era into something it wasn't. It was a time of dazzling surfaces and the rot beneath. Much like certain people I could mention.

***

### Belle Époque

The Belle Époque, a name whispered with a certain nostalgic sigh, translates to "The Beautiful Era" in French, a period of European history that supposedly bloomed after the rather unpleasant conclusion of the [Franco-Prussian War](/Franco-Prussian_War) in 1871 and withered with the infernal onset of [World War I](/World_War_I) in 1914. It coincided with the rather optimistic, if ultimately doomed, [French Third Republic](/French_Third_Republic). This era, we're told, was a champagne bubble of optimism, intellectual ferment, a surprising lull in continental warfare, economic growth that benefited, naturally, the right people, a rampant nationalism that would soon consume everything, aggressive colonial expansion, and a dizzying array of technological, scientific, and cultural breakthroughs. Paris, in particular, was supposedly the glittering epicenter of this cultural renaissance, churning out masterpieces in literature, music, theatre, and the visual arts that, conveniently, garnered widespread acclaim.

The name "Belle Époque" itself is a retrospective invention, a wistful label applied after the utter devastation of two world wars. It conjured an image of a continental European "[Golden Age](/Golden_age_(metaphor))", a stark, almost absurd contrast to the carnage that followed and the brutal finality of the [Napoleonic Wars](/Napoleonic_Wars). Historian [R. R. Palmer](/Robert_Roswell_Palmer) famously described it as a time when "[European civilisation](/Culture_of_Europe)" reached its apex of global power and exerted its "maximum influence upon peoples outside Europe." A rather grand claim, wouldn't you say? One that conveniently overlooks the boot on the neck of those very "peoples outside Europe."

#### Popular Culture and Fashions

The two cataclysmic world wars, and the subsequent grim realities they spawned, cast the Belle Époque in a rosy, almost idyllic light. It became a symbol of *joie de vivre*—a "joy of living"—a stark counterpoint to the grim 20th century. For France, it was a period of relative stability after the chaotic birth of the [Third Republic](/Third_French_Republic), which had lurched through defeat in the [Franco-Prussian War](/Franco-Prussian_War), the bloody uprising of the [Paris Commune](/Paris_Commune), and the ignominious fall of General [Georges Ernest Boulanger](/Georges_Ernest_Boulanger). Boulanger's defeat, coupled with the triumphant spectacle of the [1889 World's Fair](/Exposition_Universelle_(1889)) in Paris, supposedly ignited this era of unbridled optimism and prosperity. French [imperialism](/French_imperialism) was at its zenith, and Paris, the undisputed cultural capital of the world, boasted educational, scientific, and medical institutions that were the envy of Europe.

However, this glittering facade rarely reflected the lived reality for much of the population. France harbored a vast [underclass](/Underclass) who experienced none of the era's supposed wonders. [Poverty](/Poverty) remained a stubborn fixture in the grimy [slums](/Slums) of Paris and the impoverished [peasantry](/Peasantry) of the countryside, a reality that persisted long after the Belle Époque faded. The period was also marked by persistent friction between the government and the [Roman Catholic Church](/Roman_Catholic_Church). And let's not forget the [fin de siècle](/Fin_de_si%C3%A8cle) mood that permeated some intellectual circles, a decidedly pessimistic undercurrent that belied the outward exuberance.

The fortunate few, those who could partake in the era's prosperity, found themselves drawn to new forms of entertainment. The Parisian bourgeoisie, along with the newly minted industrialists—the *[nouveaux riches](/Nouveau_riche)*—increasingly emulated the tastes and trends of the city's elite social strata, collectively known as [Tout-Paris](/Tout-Paris) ("all of Paris," or more accurately, "everyone who mattered in Paris"). The [Casino de Paris](/Casino_de_Paris) threw open its doors in 1890, offering a taste of Parisian nightlife. For the less affluent masses, entertainment was found in the smoky confines of [cabarets](/Cabaret), [bistros](/Bistro), and [music halls](/Music_hall).

The [Moulin Rouge](/Moulin_Rouge) cabaret, a Parisian landmark still standing today, is a testament to this era's vibrant, sometimes scandalous, nightlife. The [Folies Bergère](/Folies_Bergère) was another legendary venue. [Burlesque](/Burlesque) performances, far more daring than in the prudish cities of Europe and America, were a staple. Figures like [Liane de Pougy](/Liane_de_Pougy), a dancer, [socialite](/Socialite), and renowned [courtesan](/Courtesan), captivated audiences at these top cabarets. Dancers and singers such as [Polaire](/Polaire), [Mistinguett](/Mistinguett), [Paulus](/Paulus_(singer)), [Eugénie Fougère](/Eug%C3%A9nie_Foug%C3%A8re), [La Goulue](/La_Goulue), and [Jane Avril](/Jane_Avril) became celebrated Parisian stars, some even immortalized in the iconic posters of [Toulouse-Lautrec](/Toulouse-Lautrec). The [Can-can](/Can-can) dance, a quintessential Belle Époque cabaret staple, frequently appeared in his vivid depictions of the era.

The [Eiffel Tower](/Eiffel_Tower), erected as the grand gateway to the [1889 World's Fair](/Exposition_Universelle_(1889)), swiftly became an enduring symbol of Paris, recognized globally. The city hosted another successful World's Fair in 1900, the [Exposition Universelle](/Exposition_Universelle_(1900)). Paris itself had been dramatically reshaped by the urban planning initiatives of the [Second Empire](/Second_French_Empire), particularly [Haussmann's renovation of Paris](/Haussmann%27s_renovation_of_Paris), which transformed its housing, streetscapes, and public spaces, creating the very neighborhoods that defined the Belle Époque experience.

Abundant coal and cheap labor fueled a fascination with the exotic, exemplified by the cult of the [orchid](/Orchid), and enabled the meticulous cultivation of fruits [grown under glass](/Greenhouse) for the elaborate [state dinners](/State_dinner) of the upper classes. Fashion embraced extravagance, with exotic feathers and furs adorning attire as never before. [Haute couture](/Haute_couture) was born in Paris, the very heart of the Belle Époque, initiating a yearly cycle of fashion trends. Restaurants like [Maxim's Paris](/Maxim%27s_Paris) achieved a new level of splendor and cachet, serving as stages for the wealthy to display their fortunes. Even [Bohemianism](/Bohemianism) acquired a certain glamour, finding its expression in the lively [cabarets](/Cabaret) of [Montmartre](/Montmartre).

Grand public edifices like the [Opéra Garnier](/Op%C3%A9ra_Garnier) dedicated vast interior spaces to showcase the curvilinear elegance of Art Nouveau. The expansion of [railways](/Rail_transport) connected Europe's major cities to fashionable [spa](/Spa) towns like [Biarritz](/Biarritz), [Deauville](/Deauville), [Vichy](/Vichy), [Arcachon](/Arcachon), and the [French Riviera](/French_Riviera). While carriages were strictly segregated by class, the [super-rich](/Ultra_high-net-worth_individual) began commissioning their own [private railway coaches](/Private_railroad_car), a clear indicator that exclusivity, alongside ostentatious display, was a defining characteristic of Belle Époque luxury.

#### Politics

The period between the [Franco-Prussian War](/Franco-Prussian_War) and the catastrophe of World War I was, on the surface, one of remarkable political stability in [Western](/Western_Europe) and [Central Europe](/Central_Europe). Despite the lingering animosity between France and Germany, fueled by the cession of [Alsace-Lorraine](/Alsace-Lorraine) in 1871, a series of diplomatic negotiations—the [Congress of Berlin](/Congress_of_Berlin) in 1878, the [Berlin Congo Conference](/Berlin_Conference) in 1884, and the [Algeciras Conference](/Algeciras_Conference) in 1906—managed to defuse potential conflicts. Indeed, for many Europeans of the Belle Époque, transnational, class-based affiliations often held as much sway as national identities, particularly among the aristocracy. An upper-class gentleman could traverse much of Western Europe without a [passport](/Passport) and even reside abroad with minimal bureaucratic interference. This ease of movement and national identity fluidity would soon be shattered by World War I, the advent of mass transportation, the rise of mass literacy, and evolving notions of citizenship.

The Belle Époque's economic engine relied heavily on a rigid [class structure](/Social_class) that ensured a steady supply of cheap labor. The [Paris Métro](/Paris_M%C3%A9tro), along with the [omnibus](/Bus) and [streetcar](/Streetcar), facilitated the daily commute for the working population, including the legions of [servants](/Servant) who did not reside in the affluent city centers. This daily migration contributed to suburbanization, creating a stark spatial [separation](/Income_segregation) between working-class and upper-class neighborhoods.

The [Dreyfus affair](/Dreyfus_affair) exposed deep fissures in French society. Captain [Alfred Dreyfus](/Alfred_Dreyfus), a Jewish artillery officer, was wrongly convicted of treason based on fabricated evidence. [Antisemitism](/Antisemitism), already a pervasive undercurrent in French society, became a central element of the scandal and subsequent trials. The affair ignited a firestorm of public debate, particularly after the publication of [J'Accuse…!](/J%27Accuse%E2%80%A6!), an impassioned open letter by novelist [Émile Zola](/%C3%89mile_Zola) that denounced government corruption and French antisemitism. The affair consumed national attention for years, dominating newspaper headlines and polarizing public opinion.

Meanwhile, the international workers' movement was gaining momentum, fostering pan-European, class-based identities among those whose labor underpinned the era's prosperity. The [Second International](/Second_International) emerged as a significant transnational socialist organization. [Anarchists](/Anarchism) were also active, employing tactics of [Propaganda of the deed](/Propaganda_of_the_deed). While political assassinations were less common in France than in Russia, notable incidents did occur, such as the assassination of President [Marie François Sadi Carnot](/Marie_Fran%C3%A7ois_Sadi_Carnot) in 1894. A bomb exploded in the [Chamber of Deputies of France](/Chamber_of_Deputies_of_France) in 1893, injuring several but causing no fatalities. Acts of terrorism against civilians, such as the bombing by [Émile Henry](/%C3%89mile_Henry_(anarchist)) in 1894, which killed a cafe patron and wounded others, also punctuated the period.

France itself experienced relative domestic political stability. The unexpected death of President [Félix Faure](/F%C3%A9lix_Faure) in office was a shock, but it did not destabilize the government.

Across Europe, regime changes were rare, with [Portugal](/Portugal) undergoing a [republican revolution](/5_October_1910_revolution) in 1910 being a notable exception. However, beneath the surface of apparent calm, tensions were escalating. The divide between working-class socialist movements, [bourgeois](/Bourgeoisie) [liberal](/Liberalism) parties, and the established landed aristocracy and its [conservative](/Conservatism) allies widened across many nations. This growing political instability, masked by the era's outward serenity, was a dangerous precursor to the coming conflict. The period witnessed a significant rise in [militarism](/Militarism) and international tensions, particularly between 1897 and 1914. The immediate pre-war years were characterized by a relentless [arms race](/Arms_race) across Europe. Furthermore, this era was defined by aggressive overseas [colonialism](/Colonialism), often termed the [New Imperialism](/New_Imperialism), with the [Scramble for Africa](/Scramble_for_Africa) being its most infamous manifestation.

#### Conflicts and Wars

The [pith helmet](/Pith_helmet), an enduring symbol of colonial endeavors in the world's tropical regions.
World Empires in 1900. The [British Empire](/British_Empire), painted pink, was the dominant global power, largely due to the supremacy of the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy).

The great powers, along with smaller nations like Belgium, the Netherlands, and Denmark, were deeply entangled in [imperialism](/Imperialism), carving up territories in Africa and Asia for their own overseas empires. While numerous smaller conflicts, revolutions, civil wars, and colonial uprisings occurred, some of the more significant ones during this period include the [Franco-Prussian War](/Franco-Prussian_War) (1870–1871), the [Russo-Turkish War](/Russo-Turkish_War_(1877%E2%80%931878)) (1877–1878), the [War of the Pacific](/War_of_the_Pacific) (1879–1884), the [Boer Wars](/Military_history_of_South_Africa) (1880–1881 and 1899–1902), the [First Sino-Japanese War](/First_Sino-Japanese_War) (1894–1895), the [First Italo-Ethiopian War](/First_Italo-Ethiopian_War) (1895–1896), the [Greco-Turkish War](/Greco-Turkish_War_(1897)) (1897), the [Spanish-American War](/Spanish%E2%80%93American_War) (1898), the [Philippine-American War](/Philippine%E2%80%93American_War) (1899–1902), the [Russo-Japanese War](/Russo-Japanese_War) (1905), and the [Italo-Turkish War](/Italo-Turkish_War) (1911–1912).

The [First Balkan War](/First_Balkan_War) (1912–1913) and the [Second Balkan War](/Second_Balkan_War) (1913) are often viewed as grim preludes to the devastating [First World War](/World_War_I) (1914–1918). The sheer scale of industrial-level destruction, both in terms of matériel and human lives, that characterized World War I marked the definitive end of the Belle Époque.

Beyond outright warfare, diplomatic tensions flared in several notable incidents, including the [1890 British Ultimatum](/1890_British_Ultimatum), the [Fashoda Incident](/Fashoda_Incident) (1898), the [First Moroccan Crisis](/First_Moroccan_Crisis) (1905–1906), and the [Agadir Crisis](/Agadir_Crisis) (1911). These were all sparks that threatened to ignite a larger conflagration.

#### Science and Technology

The Belle Époque was a period of exhilarating scientific and technological progress across Europe and the globe. The innovations of the [Second Industrial Revolution](/Second_Industrial_Revolution) became commonplace. The perfection of lightly sprung, silent [carriages](/Carriage) in a multitude of fashionable designs marked the early part of the era, only to be gradually eclipsed by the [automobile](/Automobile) towards its end, which remained a luxurious novelty for the affluent for its first decade. French manufacturers like [Peugeot](/Peugeot) were already established pioneers in carriage production. In the 1890s, [Edouard Michelin](/%C3%89douard_Michelin_(born_1859)) revolutionized personal transport with his invention of removable [pneumatic](/Pneumatic) [tires](/Tires) for both bicycles and automobiles. The [scooter](/Scooter_(motorcycle)) and [moped](/Moped) also emerged during this period.

Several French inventors patented innovations that continue to shape our modern world. Following the widespread adoption of the [telephone](/Telephone) and [telegraph](/Telegraph) for rapid communication, French inventor [Édouard Belin](/%C3%89douard_Belin) developed the Belinograph, or [Wirephoto](/Wirephoto), enabling the transmission of images over telephone lines. The [electric light](/Electric_light) began to supplant [gas lighting](/Gas_lighting), and in France, the invention of [neon lights](/Neon_light) added a new dimension to urban illumination.

France was at the forefront of early [cinema](/Film_industry) technology. The [cinématographe](/Cin%C3%A9matographe), invented by [Léon Bouly](/L%C3%A9on_Bouly), was famously utilized by brothers [Auguste and Louis Lumière](/Auguste_and_Louis_Lumi%C3%A8re) for the world's first film screenings. The Lumière brothers were responsible for numerous other advancements in [cinematography](/Cinematography). While [motion pictures](/Film) were developed during this era, their widespread popularity would have to wait until after World War I.

Although the [aeroplane](/Aeroplane) remained largely an experimental marvel, France was a leader in [aviation](/Aviation). In 1910, France established the world's first national [air force](/Air_force). Two French inventors, [Louis Breguet](/Louis_Breguet) and [Paul Cornu](/Paul_Cornu), independently achieved groundbreaking experiments with the first flying [helicopters](/Helicopters) in 1907.

In the realm of physics, [Henri Becquerel](/Henri_Becquerel) discovered [radioactivity](/Radioactivity) in 1896, a serendipitous finding while working with [phosphorescent](/Phosphorescent) materials. This discovery built upon earlier observations of [uranium](/Uranium) salts made by [Abel Niépce de Saint-Victor](/Abel_Ni%C3%A9pce_de_Saint-Victor) in 1857.

This period also saw significant strides in medicine and biology. Scientists and physicians finally began to grasp the [germ theory of disease](/Germ_theory_of_disease), leading to the formal establishment of the field of [bacteriology](/Bacteriology). [Louis Pasteur](/Louis_Pasteur) was arguably France's most celebrated scientist of the era, known for developing [pasteurisation](/Pasteurisation) and a groundbreaking [rabies vaccine](/Rabies_vaccine). In mathematics and physics, [Henri Poincaré](/Henri_Poincar%C3%A9) made substantial contributions to both pure and applied mathematics, and also authored accessible works on scientific and mathematical subjects for the general public. In Paris, [Marie Skłodowska-Curie](/Marie_Sk%C5%82odowska-Curie) conducted her pioneering research, earning Nobel Prizes in Physics in 1903 and Chemistry in 1911. Physicist [Gabriel Lippmann](/Gabriel_Lippmann) invented [integral imaging](/Integral_imaging), a technique still in use today.

The [Peugeot Type 3](/Peugeot_Type_3), manufactured in France in 1891, represents early automotive innovation.
A [telegraph key](/Telegraph_key), used for transmitting messages in [Morse code](/Morse_code), a vital communication tool of the era.
The sinking of the RMS Titanic in 1912, though a tragedy, became one of the most enduring and well-known events of this period.
The [Wright Flyer](/Wright_Flyer), depicted here, achieved the first sustained flight with a powered, controlled, heavier-than-air aircraft in 1903, a monumental step in aviation history.
The world's first movie poster, advertising the comedy [L'Arroseur Arrosé](/L%27Arroseur_Arros%C3%A9) in 1895, marks the nascent stage of the film industry.

#### Art and Literature

By 1890, [Vincent van Gogh](/Vincent_van_Gogh) was dead, but his paintings, largely unappreciated during his lifetime, began to garner admiration. The 1890s saw a shift in Parisian visual arts, a reaction against the prevailing ideals of the Impressionists. Post-Impressionist movements such as the [Nabis](/Les_Nabis), the [Symbolist movement](/Symbolism_(movement)) (which also influenced poetry, music, and visual art), [Fauvism](/Fauvism), and the nascent stirrings of [Modernism](/Modernism) characterized the artistic landscape. Between 1900 and 1914, [Expressionism](/Expressionism) gained traction among artists in Paris and Vienna, and early works of [Cubism](/Cubism) and [Abstraction](/Abstraction) began to appear. Foreign influences were potent, with exhibitions of Japanese printmaking profoundly impacting graphic design, particularly in posters and book illustration. Similarly, African tribal art captivated Parisian artists at the turn of the century.

The [Art Nouveau](/Art_Nouveau) style, with its distinctive curvilinear forms and nature-inspired motifs, emerged prominently in the mid-1890s and dominated progressive design across Europe, known as [Jugendstil](/Jugendstil) in Central Europe. Its application in Parisian public works, such as [Hector Guimard](/Hector_Guimard)'s iconic [Paris Métro](/Paris_M%C3%A9tro) station entrances, cemented its association with the city.

Notable artists working in Paris during the Belle Époque included post-Impressionists like [Odilon Redon](/Odilon_Redon), [Gustave Moreau](/Gustave_Moreau), [Maurice Denis](/Maurice_Denis), [Pierre Bonnard](/Pierre_Bonnard), [Édouard Vuillard](/%C3%89douard_Vuillard), [Paul Gauguin](/Paul_Gauguin), [Henri Matisse](/Henri_Matisse), [Émile Bernard](/%C3%89mile_Bernard_(painter)), [Henri Rousseau](/Henri_Rousseau), and [Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec](/Henri_de_Toulouse-Lautrec). The reputation of Toulouse-Lautrec, in particular, grew significantly after his death. [Auguste Rodin](/Auguste_Rodin), a native Parisian, redefined modern sculpture with his powerful works. Even a young [Pablo Picasso](/Pablo_Picasso) was making his mark on the Parisian art scene.

While [Impressionism](/Impressionism) had emerged well before the Belle Époque, it initially faced public skepticism, accustomed as it was to the Academy-sanctioned realism. Monet's series of [Haystacks](/Haystacks_(Monet)) began in 1890. Though considered avant-garde in the 1860s, Impressionism only gained widespread acceptance after World War I. Academic painting, dictated by the Parisian Academy of Art, remained the most respected style among the public. Artists like [William-Adolphe Bouguereau](/William-Adolphe_Bouguereau), the English [Pre-Raphaelite](/Pre-Raphaelite_Brotherhood)'s [John William Waterhouse](/John_William_Waterhouse), and [Lord Leighton](/Frederic_Leighton,_1st_Baron_Leighton) with his idyllic Roman scenes, catered to more traditional tastes. Progressive patrons, however, supported the [Barbizon school](/Barbizon_school) painters who worked *en plein air*, often associated with the Pre-Raphaelites and inspiring a generation of aesthetically inclined "[Souls](/The_Souls)".

Art Nouveau found numerous expressions across France and beyond, with notable regional variations appearing in [Germany](/Germany), [Belgium](/Belgium), [Spain](/Spain), [Austria](/Austria) (through the [Vienna Secession](/Vienna_Secession)), [Hungary](/Hungary), [Bohemia](/Bohemia), [Serbia](/Serbia), and [Latvia](/Latvia). Its influence spread globally, reaching [Peru](/Peru), [Brazil](/Brazil), [Argentina](/Argentina), [Mexico](/Mexico), and the [United States](/United_States).

[European literature](/European_literature) underwent a profound transformation. [Literary realism](/Literary_realism) and [naturalism](/Naturalism_(literature)) reached their zenith with authors like the French [Guy de Maupassant](/Guy_de_Maupassant) and [Émile Zola](/%C3%89mile_Zola). Gradually, realism evolved into [modernism](/Modernism), which emerged in the 1890s and dominated European literature in the Belle Époque's final years and into the [interwar years](/Interwar_period). [Marcel Proust](/Marcel_Proust) began his monumental modernist work, *[In Search of Lost Time](/In_Search_of_Lost_Time)*, in 1909, to be published after World War I. The works of German author [Thomas Mann](/Thomas_Mann), such as *[Death in Venice](/Death_in_Venice)* (1912), resonated deeply in France. [Colette](/Colette) caused a stir with her sexually candid *[Claudine](/Claudine_(book_series))* novels. [Joris-Karl Huysmans](/Joris-Karl_Huysmans), a prominent figure in the 1880s, continued to explore themes associated with [Symbolism](/Symbolism_(arts)) and the [Decadent movement](/Decadent_movement), most notably in his novel *[à rebours](/%C3%80_rebours)*. [André Gide](/Andr%C3%A9_Gide), [Anatole France](/Anatole_France), [Alain-Fournier](/Alain-Fournier), and [Paul Bourget](/Paul_Bourget) were among France's most popular fiction writers of the era.

A vibrant 1894 poster by [Jules Chéret](/Jules_Ch%C3%A9ret) captures the effervescent spirit of the Belle Époque.

Symbolist poets like [Charles Baudelaire](/Charles_Baudelaire), whose collection *[Les Fleurs du mal](/Les_Fleurs_du_mal)* was published in the 1850s, continued to exert a powerful influence. The Decadent movement fascinated Parisians, captivated by poets such as [Paul Verlaine](/Paul_Verlaine) and, especially, [Arthur Rimbaud](/Arthur_Rimbaud), who became the quintessential *enfant terrible*. Rimbaud's *[Illuminations](/Illuminations_(poetry_collection))* was published in 1886, followed by his other works, influencing [Surrealists](/Surrealism) and [Modernists](/Modernism) during and after the Belle Époque. Rimbaud's poetry introduced the French public to the concept of [free verse](/Free_verse). This experimentation extended to typography, as seen in [Stéphane Mallarmé](/St%C3%A9phane_Mallarm%C3%A9)'s *[Un coup de dés jamais n'abolira le hasard](/Un_coup_de_d%C3%A9s_jamais_n%27abolira_le_hasard_(Mallarm%C3%A9))*, which foreshadowed [Dada](/Dada) and [concrete poetry](/Concrete_poetry). [Guillaume Apollinaire](/Guillaume_Apollinaire)'s poetry brought themes and imagery from modern life to readers. The international review *[Cosmopolis: An International Monthly Review](/Cosmopolis_(magazine))* significantly impacted European writers, with editions published in London, Paris, Saint Petersburg, and Berlin.

Parisian bourgeois theatre thrived on the light farces of [Georges Feydeau](/Georges_Feydeau) and [cabaret](/Cabaret) performances. Theatre embraced new, modern approaches, including Expressionism, and playwrights often shocked audiences with their frank portrayals of life and sexuality or their innovative artistic elements. Cabaret theatre itself gained considerable popularity.

Musically, the Belle Époque was characterized by [salon music](/Salon_music)—short, accessible pieces for piano or violin and piano, and a rich repertoire of songs. Italian composers, particularly [Francesco Paolo Tosti](/Francesco_Paolo_Tosti), were masters of this genre, though its popularity waned over time. Waltzes also enjoyed widespread popularity, as did [operettas](/Operetta) by composers such as [Johann Strauss III](/Johann_Strauss_III), [Emmerich Kálmán](/Emmerich_K%C3%A1lm%C3%A1n), and [Franz Lehár](/Franz_Leh%C3%A1r). Many composers active in Paris during this era remain celebrated today, including [Igor Stravinsky](/Igor_Stravinsky), [Erik Satie](/Erik_Satie), [Claude Debussy](/Claude_Debussy), [Lili Boulanger](/Lili_Boulanger), [Jules Massenet](/Jules_Massenet), [César Franck](/C%C3%A9sar_Franck), [Camille Saint-Saëns](/Camille_Saint-Sa%C3%ABns), [Gabriel Fauré](/Gabriel_Faur%C3%A9), and his student [Maurice Ravel](/Maurice_Ravel). [Edvard Grieg](/Edvard_Grieg) was particularly favored in Parisian concert halls and salons, despite his controversial stance in the Dreyfus affair. Ravel and [Frederick Delius](/Frederick_Delius) acknowledged Grieg's influence, with Ravel famously remarking that French music of the time was "Edvard Grieg plus the third act of Tristan."

The emergence of [modern dance](/Modern_dance) marked a significant artistic development in theatre. Dancer [Loie Fuller](/Loie_Fuller) captivated audiences at venues like the [Folies Bergère](/Folies_Berg%C3%A8re) and toured internationally. Sergei Diaghilev's [Ballets Russes](/Ballets_Russes) brought fame to dancers like [Vaslav Nijinsky](/Vaslav_Nijinsky) and established new standards in ballet technique. The Ballets Russes premiered masterpieces such as *[The Firebird](/The_Firebird)* and *[The Rite of Spring](/The_Rite_of_Spring)*, the latter famously inciting audience riots.

